WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.376
Start with system instructions at the right altitude.

2
00:00:02.848 --> 00:00:07.682
At one extreme, a prompt hard-codes every branch with brittle if-else logic.

3
00:00:07.174 --> 00:00:13.559
At the other, it says something vague like do a great job and assumes the Agent shares your unstated expectations.

4
00:00:13.052 --> 00:00:18.569
The useful middle gives clear goals, boundaries, and heuristics while leaving room to reason.

5
00:00:18.018 --> 00:00:24.458
Organize background, instructions, tool guidance, and output expectations into distinct sections.

6
00:00:23.913 --> 00:00:29.074
The formatting helps, but the decisive value is the clarity and priority of the content.

7
00:00:28.599 --> 00:00:30.933
Next, inspect the tools.

8
00:00:30.411 --> 00:00:35.389
A tool is not only an action; it is a contract between the Agent and its environment.

9
00:00:34.845 --> 00:00:42.718
Names, descriptions, parameters, error behavior, and returned data all enter context and shape which action the Agent chooses.

10
00:00:42.261 --> 00:00:46.249
Overlapping tools create ambiguous decisions and waste attention.

11
00:00:45.671 --> 00:00:53.149
If a human cannot clearly explain when to use one tool instead of another, the Agent is unlikely to resolve the ambiguity reliably.

12
00:00:52.606 --> 00:00:58.921
Keep a minimal viable set, return token-efficient results, and let each tool do one understandable job.

13
00:00:58.386 --> 00:01:00.316
Then curate examples.

14
00:00:59.811 --> 00:01:04.597
A long catalogue of edge cases feels comprehensive, but it can bury the pattern.

15
00:01:04.051 --> 00:01:12.356
Anthropic recommends a small, diverse set of canonical examples that show the expected behavior, important variation, and a meaningful boundary.

16
00:01:11.861 --> 00:01:14.618
High signal is not a fixed token count.

17
00:01:14.091 --> 00:01:23.723
It is information with a clear job: establish the outcome, constrain behavior, select a tool, demonstrate a pattern, provide evidence, or expose a stop condition.

18
00:01:23.155 --> 00:01:26.730
Remove material only when it performs none of those jobs.

19
00:01:26.266 --> 00:01:30.619
First, write instructions at the right altitude between brittle and vague.

20
00:01:30.168 --> 00:01:34.618
Second, keep tools clear, efficient, and minimally overlapping.

21
00:01:34.111 --> 00:01:38.109
Third, teach the pattern with a small set of canonical examples.
